==Playing time== In order to meet the requirements of the television broadcasters, the [[Australian Football League|AFL]] adjusted the playing time allocated to each of a match's four quarters for this season. Playing time was reduced from 25 minutes to 20 minutes, however some additional stoppages attracted "time-on" allocations; the total reduction of playing time was approximately 10%.
==Awards== * The [[Brownlow Medal]] was awarded to [[Greg Williams (Australian footballer)|Greg Williams]] of {{AFL Car}}. * The [[Leigh Matthews Trophy]] was awarded to [[Greg Williams (Australian footballer)|Greg Williams]] of {{AFL Car}}. * The [[Coleman Medal]] was awarded to [[Gary Ablett, Sr.|Gary Ablett]] of {{AFL Gee}}. * The [[Norm Smith Medal]] was awarded to [[Dean Kemp]] of {{AFL WC}}. * The [[AFL Rising Star]] award was awarded to [[Chris Scott (Australian footballer)|Chris Scott]] of {{AFL BB}}. * The [[Wooden Spoon (award)|Wooden Spoon]] was "awarded" to {{AFL Syd}}.
==Notable events== * The AFL increases the number of interchange players to three which, when added to the "run on" team of 18 on-the-field players, increasing the standard team squad size to 21 players. * The "[[blood rule]]" was introduced in order to allay fears raised by the threat of [[AIDS]]. * The AFL introduced a third field umpire. * The reduction in a match's amount of elapsed playing time (see above). * The [[McIntyre System#Second McIntyre final six system|Second McIntyre "Final Six" system]], which had operated in 1992 and 1993, was replaced by the [[McIntyre System#McIntyre final eight system|McIntyre "Final Eight" system]]. The McIntyre "Final Eight" system operated from 1994 to 1999; it was replaced by the [[AFL finals system|AFLâs Amended "Final Eight" system]] in 2000. * The third qualifying final between {{AFL Nor}} and {{AFL Haw}} was the first ever [[Australian Football League|AFL]] game to require [[extra time]], after the teams were tied at 91 after four quarters. The provision for extra time was introduced after the controversial [[1990 AFL season|1990]] finals series, where the qualifying final between {{AFL Col}} and {{AFL WC}} was tied, forcing a replay the following weekend which gave top team {{AFL Ess}} a second bye weekend. North Melbourne dominated extra time and won the game by 23 points.
